"Cocks L.R.M., Jia-Yu R.","Earliest Silurian faunal survival and recovery after the end Ordovician glaciation: Evidence from the brachiopods",2007,"Earth and Environmental Science Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh","98","3-4",,"291","301",,,10.1017/S175569100807566X,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-54749149103&partnerID=40&md5=0a11523f5cc0889da03e241b32268993","Department of Palaeontology, The Natural History Museum, London SW7 5BD, United Kingdom; Institute of Geology and Palaeontology, Academia Sinica, 39 East Beijing Road, Nanjing 210008, China","Cocks, L.R.M., Department of Palaeontology, The Natural History Museum, London SW7 5BD, United Kingdom; Jia-Yu, R., Institute of Geology and Palaeontology, Academia Sinica, 39 East Beijing Road, Nanjing 210008, China","Earliest Silurian (basal Llandovery) brachiopod faunas are surveyed and listed from around the globe, and divided between Lower Rhuddanian and Upper Rhuddanian occurrences. 60 genera are known from the Lower Rhuddanian within 20 superfamilies and there are 87 genera in 25 superfamilies in the Upper Rhuddanian. The 29 areas surveyed span the globe, both latitudinally and longitudinally. Only six superfamilies are Lazarus taxa which are known both from the Ordovician and Middle Llandovery (Aeronian) and later rocks but have not been recorded from the Rhuddanian. These are surprising results, since many previous studies have inferred that the Rhuddanian was a time of very sparse faunas. The global warming that followed the latest Ordovician (Hirnantian) ice age did not proceed quickly, with an ice-cap probably present through at least the Llandovery. There is a marked absence of Lower Rhuddanian bioherms even at low palaeolatitudes; however, the ecological recovery rate was far faster than that following the end-Permian mass extinction event. The partitioning of the Rhuddanian shelf faunas into well-defined benthic assemblages progressed slowly over the interval. © 2008 Royal Society of Edinburgh.","Llandovery; Post-glacial recovery; Rhuddanian",,,,,,,"Amsden, T.W., Late Ordovician and Early Silurian articulate brachiopods from Oklahoma, southwestern Illinois, and eastern Mississippi (1974) Oklahoma Geological Survey Bulletin, 119, pp. 1-54; (1991) Atlas of fossil faunas and floras of Tadzhikistan. Ordovican, Silurian, Devonian, , Babayeva, V. S, Dzhalilov, N. R, Melnikova, G. K, Sabirov, A. A. Salibayev, G. K. & Khakimov, F. K, eds, 272 pp. Donish, Dushanbe, In Russian; Baarli, G.B., Benthic faunal associations in the Lower Silurian Solvik Formation of the Oslo-Asker Districts, Norway (1987) Lethaia, 20, pp. 75-90; Baarli, G.B., The Llandovery enteletacean brachiopods of the central Oslo region, Norway (1988) Palaeontology, 31, pp. 1101-1129; Baarli, G.B., Orthacean and strophomenid brachiopods from the Lower Silurian of the central Oslo Region (1995) Fossils and Strata, 39, pp. 1-93; Baarli, G.B., Harper, D.A.T., Relict Ordovician brachiopod faunas in the Lower Silurian of Asker, Oslo Region, Norway (1986) Norsk Geologisk Tiddskrift, 66, pp. 87-98; Benedetto, J.L., Braquiopodos del Silurico temprano malvino-cafrico (Formacion La Chilca), Precordillera Argentina (1995) Geobios, 28, pp. 425-457; Bergstrom, S.M., Boucot, A.J., The Ordovician-Silurian boundary in the United States (1988) Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Geology, 43, pp. 273-284; Beznosova, T.M., (1994) Stratigraphy and brachiopods of the Silurian of northeast European Russia, , 127 pp. St Petersburg, Nauka, In Russian; Beznosova, T.M., Silurian brachiopod biostratigraphy, NE Timan - N Urals, Russia (1996) Brachiopods, pp. 35-40. , Copper, P. & Jin, J, eds, Rotterdam: Balkema; Borisiak, M.A., Lower Llandovery brachiopods from northeast Kazakhstan (1964) Trudy Paleontologia i Stratigrafia VSEGEI, 93, pp. 71-80. , In Russian; Boucot, A.J., Johnson, J.G., Shagam, R., Braquipodos siluricos de los Andes meridenos de Venezuela (1972) Boletin de Geologia Publicacion